    // do something with *it
    ++it;
}
```

2. **Range-based for loop**: This is a more modern and idiomatic way to iterate over a `std::list`.

    ```cpp
for (const auto& elem : my_list) {
    // do something with elem
}
```

3. **Member functions**: You can use the member functions `begin()` and `end()` to get iterators pointing to the beginning and end of the list, respectively.

    ```cpp
auto it = my_list.begin();
while (it != my_list.end()) {
    // do something with *it
    ++it;
}
```

4. **std::for_each**: This function applies a given function to each element in the list.

    ```cpp
std::for_each(my_list.begin(), my_list.end(),
               [](const auto& elem) { /* do something with elem */ });
```

5. **std::copy**: This function copies elements from one range into another.

    ```cpp
std::copy(my_list.begin(), my_list.end(), std::ostream_iterator<char>(cout));
```

6. **std::transform**: This function applies a given function to each element in the list and stores the results in another range.

    ```cpp
std::transform(my_list.begin(), my_list.end(),
                [](const auto& elem) { /* do something with elem */ },
                std::ostream_iterator<char>(cout));
```

